<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Reduces Curfew Hours in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The west Africa peace-keeping
force ECOMOG has reduced the curfew hours in Sierra Leone to
between midnight and 6 a.m., a report reaching here said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made in view of the improved security in the
west Africa country, the report said, adding that the new curfew
duration has been confirmed by ECOMOG troops manning a checkpoint
in the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG imposed a curfew from 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. in early
February after it captured the Freetown peninsula from the
military junta of Major Johnny Paul Koromah.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG announced Wednesday that it had captured Sierra Leone's
second largest city Bo from troops loyal to Koromah, who has been
in hide after ECOMOG captured Freetown two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Fighting is now continuing in the interior areas of Sierra
Leone, including Kenema, a diamond-producing city in eastern part
of the country.
</P>
<P>
As ECOMOG is consolidating its control, outsted president
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, who has been in exile in neighboring Guinea
since Koromah's coup last May, is expected to return to Sierra
Leone to resume office soon. 
</P>
