<HEADLINE> Uganda's Foreign Reserves Increase Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's foreign reserves is
expected to reach 707.87 million U.S. Dollars by the end of June
this year, compared with 479.70 million and 626.59 million U.S.
Dollars at the same time of 1996 and 1997 respectively, a local
report said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Damoni Kitabire, acting director of budget in Finance
Ministry, was quoted as saying that the increase is reflected by
the high GDP growth rate which averaged 6.5 percent over the last
ten fiscal years and 7.9 percent over the past ten years.
</P>
<P>
Kitabir also attributed the reserves growth to the granting to
Uganda of a multi-lateral debt relief under the Highly Indebted
Poor Countries (HIPC) debt relief initiative.
</P>
<P>
The level of foreign exchange reserves at the Bank of Uganda
has been displaying strong growth, he added.
</P>
<P>
In line with the economic development, the exchange rate of
the country's currency is stable in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The foreign reserves of the country are at the level of an
approximately five months of its imports of goods and non-factor
services, Kitabire added. In 1992-1993 fiscal year, the reserves
of the country could only cover some two months imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
