<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Exports, Imports Decline in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's exports
and imports all declined in January 1998 on a year-on-year basis,
according to a release published here Friday by the Census and
Statistics Department.
</P>
<P>
Total exports in January decreased by 4.1 percent over a year
earlier to 114.4 billion HK dollars (14.7 billion U.S. dollars).
Re-exports went down slightly by 2.9 percent to 99.1 billion HK
dollars (12.7 billion U.S. dollars), while domestic exports slid
by 11 percent to 15.3 billion HK dollars (two billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Total imports slumped by 14 percent from a year before to 113.2
billion HK dollars (14.5 billion U.S. dollars) in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
A visible trade surplus of 1.2 billion HK dollars (154 million
U.S. dollars) was recorded in the first month this year, in
contrast to a deficit of 12.4 billion HK dollars (1.6 billion U.S.
dollars) in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman pointed out that the trade figures
usually displayed greater volatility in the first two months of
the year. He attributed the year-on-year declines in exports and
imports in January 1998 to the different timing of the Spring
Festival in 1997 and 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
