<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California to Get Government Funds For El Nino Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government will
allocate an estimated 250 million U.S. dollars to California to
compensate the damage caused by El Nino, said officials from the
Federal Emergency Management Agency Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Twenty million dollars of the funds will be used to help repair
highways and buildings torn up by rain and mud slides, said James
Lee Witt, director of the agency, who is making a survey into the
disaster.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino resulted in serious storms, floods and mudslides in
the state, having brought about approximately 500 million dollars
worth of property damage since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is now in California meeting with local
officials and citizens to discuss recovering efforts.
</P>
<P>
The National Weather Service said that, in the first 24 days of
February, the Los Angeles civic center received 13.38 inches of
rain, the most since records started being kept in 1877.
</P>
<P>
San Francisco is experiencing the wettest winter in this
century with a total rainfall of 38.48 inches received during this
season.
</P>
<P>
El Nino has already been blamed for 90 deaths across the United
States since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Joe Friday, chief analyst in the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), said this figure surpasses the
death toll in the 1982-83 El Nino, which had been the strongest
one ever studied.
</P>
<P>
Forecasters have warned that the El Nino weather phenomenon
will continue raging through late spring.
</P>
<P>
"El Nino will remain the same for the next two to three months
at least," said Vernon Kousky, another senior chief analyst in
NOAA, adding that it was impossible to tell if the worst was over
or if even more violent weather is on the way. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
