<HEADLINE> Shanghailanders Exhibit Changing Consumer Psychology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 27 (Xinhua) -- "Need" and "brand"
have replaced "price" as the most important factor influencing the
shopping decisions of Shanghailanders, according to a survey by
the Shanghai Statistics Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The survey revealed that 64 percent of 500 urban families
questioned pay little attention to discounts, but instead equate
price with quality.
</P>
<P>
Fourteen percent cited "need" as the reason for purchasing
color television sets and air conditioners during 1997, with
less than eight percent citing low prices.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of customers are paying more attention to
brand name goods, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute changing shopping habits to the maturation of
the local consumer psychology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
