<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Enjoys Falling Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Retail prices in Guangzhou,
the capital of Guangdong Province and south China's leading
industrial center, dropped by 0.6 percent in 1997, following
annual increases since 1991.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou City Price Bureau reported that the price index
rose by an average 12.7 percent between 1991-1996, a level
significantly lower than the 19.38 percent growth rate for its
gross domestic product (GDP) -- the value of goods and services
produced.
</P>
<P>
Statistics indicate that prices for each of the first 10 months
of 1997 fell when compared to the previous year's corresponding
periods.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that four consecutive bumper harvests and controls
exercised by the city government contributed to falling
prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
