<DOCNO> XIE19980227.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Concerned about Continued Violence in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 26 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council remains gravely concerned about the continued violence in
Sierra Leone and on Thursday called for the immediate restoration
of President Tejan Kabbah's government.
</P>
<P>
The Council said in a presidential statement that it expressed
its deep regret at the loss of life and property and immense
suffering of the people of Sierra Leone since a military coup
took place on May 25, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Council commended the important role of the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) for the peaceful
solution of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
It encouraged the Military Observer Group of ECOWAS (ECOMOG) to
proceed in its efforts to foster peace and stability in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
It stressed the need for close cooperation between the
legitimate government of Sierra Leone, ECOWAS, ECOMOG commanders,
the special envoy of U.N. Secretary-General, U.N. agencies and
relevant international bodies in their work.
</P>
<P>
The Council supported the idea of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan to take rapid steps towards the reopening of the U.N.
Liaison Office in the capital of Freedom in order to assist the
national reconciliation and political dialogue in that country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
