<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish FM Hold Talks with Jordanian leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 26 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail
Cem, who arrived here Thursday for a two-day official visit, held
talks with King Hussein of Jordan and other senior officials on
Mideast peace and bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's official news agency Petra reported that the two sides
reviewed the Middle East peace process and ways to push it forward
during the meetings held between Cem and Hussein, Crown Prince
Hassan, Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali and other Jordanian
officials.
</P>
<P>
The king affirmed the importance of implementing agreements
signed between the Palestinians and Israelis with a view to enter
the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Hussein also stressed the need for concerted efforts to achieve
a comprehensive and permanent peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the king emphasized the "distinguished strong ties"
between Jordan and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also discussed the ways to promote bilateral economic
cooperation in the future.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also covered the agreement reached Monday between
Iraq and the United Nations over arms inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
